Microscopically, cat A exhibited a florid nasal luminal exudate of neutrophils intermixed with fibrin, sloughed epithelial cells and mucus (Fig. 1
). The epithelium was intact, but attenuated in some areas. Submucosal inflammation comprised a mixed population of neutrophils, lymphocytes and plasma cells with macrophages. In some areas, the inflammatory process disrupted the underlying bone. Meningeal infiltration of neutrophils, lymphocytes, plasma cells and occasional macrophages intermixed with fibrin and oedema fluid was observed (Fig. 2
). The inflammation tended to be more intense around blood vessels and extended into the underlying neuropil in some areas. In both the nasal passages and the meninges, gram-positive cocci arranged in pairs and chains were demonstrated by Gram stain (Fig. 3
). Staining of serial sections by periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) did not reveal the presence of fungi. Microscopical changes compatible with herpesvirus infection were not observed.
